i used jfor to generate rtf.

On 10/14/05, James Abley &lt;james.abley@...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;  On 14/10/05, Balraj Goulikar &lt;gbalraj@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Mark,
&gt; &gt; The viewers (in my case the client) are forcing me for another format.
&gt; rtf
&gt; &gt; of pdf or document.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; i took a short cut. i am using the xml file generated by junit report
&gt; and
&gt; &gt; processing it.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; this one calls org.apache.xalan.xslt.Process.main(pass);
&gt; &gt; &lt;target name=&quot;genXSLTCFO&quot; depends=&quot;testresults&quot;&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;echo&gt;&quot;XSLFO for the tests&quot;&lt;/echo&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;java classname=&quot;test.custom.TestsProcess&quot; fork=&quot;yes&quot; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;classpath refid=&quot;project.class.path.client&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/java&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;echo&gt;&quot;XSLFO for the summary of tests&quot;&lt;/echo&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;java classname=&quot;test.custom.SummaryProcess&quot; fork=&quot;yes&quot; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;classpath refid=&quot;project.class.path.client&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/java&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/target&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; this one calls org.jfor.jfor.main.CmdLineConverter.main(pass);
&gt; &gt; &lt;target name=&quot;generateRTF&quot; depends=&quot;genXSLTCFO&quot;&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;echo&gt;&quot;RTF for the tests&quot;&lt;/echo&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;java classname=&quot;test.custom.TestsCmdLineConverter&quot; fork=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;classpath refid=&quot;project.class.path.client&quot; /&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/java&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;echo&gt;&quot;RTF for the summary of tests&quot;&lt;/echo&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;java classname=&quot;test.custom.SummaryCmdLineConverter&quot; fork=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;classpath refid=&quot;project.class.path.client&quot; /&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/java&gt;
&gt; &gt; &lt;/target&gt;
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; i am doing probably the same thing what junit report task does. use xml
&gt; &gt; and
&gt; &gt; xsl (frames and no frames) and make it html.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Have you considered using Apache FOP? That should give you RTF and PDF
&gt; options.
&gt;
&gt; James
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; On 10/14/05, Mark Salter &lt;marksalter@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Balraj Goulikar wrote:
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; nobody wud want to sit and save as every report into
&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; word doc. probaby one more similar ant task with a bit of changes?
&gt; &gt; &gt; You could write some code in VBA to run in Word which could open each
&gt; &gt; &gt; html file in a directory, and then save as a word document, but why
&gt; &gt; &gt; would you?
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Can you explain why you want the results in &#39;word&#39;, why force your
&gt; &gt; &gt; viewers to use word, when a browser of their choice could suffice?
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I think it would take more than a &#39;bit&#39; of changes to translate html
&gt; &gt; &gt; into the ever changing, and probably badly documented microsoft &#39;word&#39;
&gt; &gt; &gt; file format.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
